docs.abstract: Her character, a glamorous singer, might remind others of Diana Ross, but that’s not what the star was thinking. Really.
docs.snippet: Her character, a glamorous singer, might remind others of Diana Ross, but that’s not what the star was thinking. Really.
docs.lead_paragraph: Tracee Ellis Ross can’t dance — at least, not the kind of dancing that requires following choreography in three-inch heels while belting disco-pop into a microphone. She learned this the hard way, preparing for “The High Note,” a new comedy out Friday on video on demand. She plays Grace Davis, a superstar singer looking for a refresh; enter her striving personal assistant (Dakota Johnson) who dreams of being a producer.

headline.main: What Tracee Ellis Ross Worried About in ‘High Note’ (It Wasn’t Her Mom)
headline.print_headline: Tracee Ellis Ross Didn’t Have Mom on Her Mind

docs.snippet: Libre, a Spanish-language supplement included in El Nuevo Herald, a sibling to The Miami Herald, published a column comparing Black Lives Matter activists to “Nazi thugs.”
docs.lead_paragraph: The Miami Herald, one of the country’s largest newspapers, apologized on Monday for a column it called “incredibly offensive” that appeared last week in Libre, a paid Spanish-language insert included with copies of El Nuevo Herald, a sibling publication.

headline.main: Miami Herald Editor Apologizes for ‘Racist and Anti-Semitic’ Insert
